! title: A ransomware attack delivered by a phishing email
! author: Exercise adapted from NCSC 'Exercise-in-a-Box'
! summary
This scenario presents a common method that attackers use to infect an organisation with ransomware.
It will help you understand how well-meaning users can fall victim to phishing attacks and what the consequences of that are.
Additionally, it covers your response in the case of a successful attack, and your ability to recover critical business data from backups.


@ Inject 1: Initial phishing
! content
Your finance team have received an email from a customer, below, stating they've attempted to make a payment but are having trouble.
The email comes from a different address than the customer typically uses, containing only a slight misspelling of the customer's name.
%(https://ttxgym.com/lib/exercise_data/phish_screenshot.png)

# discussion
+ What mechanisms does your organisation have in place to make it difficult for attackers to reach your users — both technical controls such as email filtering and domain authentication, and human controls such as user awareness training?
+ Is there a documented procedure for what a user should do if they suspect an email is malicious? Is that procedure easy to find and follow in the moment?
+ Do users feel comfortable reporting a suspected phishing attack — including one they may have already fallen for — without fear of blame?
# prompts
+ Encourage the group to think beyond spam filters. A convincing email may still reach an inbox if it comes from a compromised legitimate account or passes authentication checks. What happens when the technical controls don't catch it?
+ Probe whether awareness training is genuinely embedded in culture or treated as a box-ticking exercise. Ask how the organisation measures whether training is effective.
+ If participants are unsure about specific controls, note these as gaps to follow up after the exercise.
