@ Inject 3: User permissions
! content
When the attached file is opened, it immediately attempts to infect the computer with malware.
The infection starts with the same permissions as the user, which gives it the same access level as the user.

# discussion
+ Are users given only the access they need to perform their role, or do most users have broad access to systems and data? Do any standard accounts have local administrator privileges?
+ What happens when a user attempts to install new software — is this permitted by default, or does it require approval?
+ Does your organisation use application whitelisting or similar controls to restrict which programmes are permitted to execute on your systems?
# prompts
+ Ask participants to consider specifically what the malware would have been able to reach given the permissions of a typical finance team member — shared drives, customer data, financial records.
+ The principle of least privilege is often poorly implemented in practice. Acknowledge the tension between security and operational convenience: the goal is deliberate, documented decisions about access — not locking everything down.
+ If permissions have not been reviewed recently, flag this as a priority action to take forward after the exercise.
? We place appropriate limits on the software that can be installed or run on our organisation's IT.
+ Not at all confident
+ Slightly confident
+ Somewhat confident
+ Fairly confident
+ Completely confident

@ Inject 4: Ransomware and backups
! content
After several hours, users have started having trouble opening documents and files.
A message pops up on the computer where the infected software was installed, indicating it has been infected with ransomware.
The ransomware has encrypted all of your organisation's business-critical data, so that you can no longer access them and is demanding £150,000 in cryptocurrency to recover the data.

# discussion
+ Do you have a tested incident response plan that covers ransomware? When was it last reviewed, who is responsible for executing it, and — critically — is it accessible if your systems are unavailable?
+ What data is backed up and how frequently? Are your backups genuinely isolated from your main systems, so that an attacker who reached your network could not also encrypt or delete them?
+ How long would it take to restore your data from backups, and has this been tested under realistic conditions?
# prompts
+ Use the £150,000 ransom figure deliberately — ask participants directly whether they would pay, and what factors would drive that decision. Paying does not guarantee recovery and may invite further attacks.
+ The most common backup failure is untested restoration. Ask not just whether backups exist, but how long recovery actually took the last time it was tested.
+ Flag any legal or regulatory obligations raised here — such as GDPR breach notification — as a lead-in to the next stage on communications.
? We have identified our critical systems and data and understand the potential impact of an infection.
