@ Inject 5: Ransomware response and communication
! content
Your organisation begins to receive calls from journalists requesting information on rumours that you are suffering from a ransomware attack.
Over the next few hours stories begin to appear on social media and local industry press suggesting that your organisation has suffered from a ransomware attack.

# discussion
+ Does your organisation have a pre-prepared communications plan for a cyber incident, including a designated spokesperson and a holding statement that can be issued while the situation is still being assessed?
+ In what order would you communicate — to staff, customers and partners, regulators, and the media? What are the risks of getting that order wrong?
+ What are your regulatory obligations for notifying affected parties and relevant authorities, and are these understood by the people who would be managing the response?
# prompts
+ Use the journalist scenario to make the pressure feel real: the organisation is no longer controlling the narrative. Ask how participants would respond right now, before any holding statement exists.
+ Remind the group that GDPR requires notification to the ICO within 72 hours of becoming aware of a personal data breach — this runs in parallel with the technical response, regardless of how chaotic things are.
+ Probe whether the communications plan and contact details are held offline. A plan stored only on the network is inaccessible during a ransomware attack.
+ Close the exercise by summarising the key themes and gaps identified across all five stages, and agree on priority actions to take forward.
? We have a clear and consistent approach for communication with staff, media and stakeholders during an incident.
